 Partch is still regularly called a "hobo composer." Yet few have questioned this label's impact on his musical output, compositional life, and reception. Focusing on Partch the person alongside the cultural icon he represented, this study examines Partch from historical, cultural, political, and musical perspectives. It outlines the cultural history of the hobo from the mid-1800s through the 1960s, as well as those figures associated with the hobo's image. It explores how Partch's music, which chronicled a disappearing subculture, was received, and how the composer ultimately engaged and frustrated popular conceptions of the hobo. And it follows Partch's later years to question his response to the hobo label and the ways in which others used it to define and contain him for over thirty years S. Andrew Granade is Associate Professor of Musicology in the Conservatory of Music and Dance, University of Missouri-Kansas City.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aComposerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aHobo songsxHistory and criticism. 4aModern History. 4aMusic. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Composers & Musicians.2bisacsh  aGreat Depression.  aHarry Partch.  aS. Andrew Granade.  aUniversity of Missouri-Kansas City.  acultural history of the hobo.  acultural icon.  ahobo label.  ahobo years.  asubculture.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311143136940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978158046865740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781580468657423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781580468657/original  a978-3-11-143136-9  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles